            "title": "Too Many Ifs? 🤯",
            "content": "If you are checking one variable against many values, `if...else if` can get messy.\n\nUse a `switch` statement instead!"
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l5_2",
            "type": "quiz",
            "title": "Quick Check 🧠",
            "content": "",
            "quizData": {
                "id": "q_l5_1",
                "type": "multiple_choice",
                "question": "When is `switch` useful?",
                "options": [
                    {
                        "id": "opt1",
                        "text": "For checking ranges",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt2",
                        "text": "For checking many specific values",
                        "isCorrect": true
                    }
                ],
                "explanation": "It's cleaner than many `else if` for specific value checks."
            }
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l5_3",
            "type": "code",
            "title": "Switch Syntax 🎛️",
            "content": "Check `fruit` against cases.",
            "codeSnippet": "let fruit = 'apple';\n\nswitch(fruit) {\n  case 'banana':\n    console.log('Yellow!');\n    break;\n  case 'apple':\n    console.log('Red!');\n    break;\n  default:\n    console.log('Unknown');\n}",
            "codeLanguage": "javascript",
            "canRunCode": true
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l5_4",
            "type": "tip",
            "title": "Don't forget Break! 🛑",
            "content": "## Stop the fall\n\nYou need the `break` keyword at the end of each `case`.\n\nOtherwise, it will 'fall through' and run the next case too!"
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l5_5",
            "type": "quiz",
